SIMPLE: turbid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turbid
<hw>Tur"bid</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucir⟧r"b⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>turbidus</ets>, from <ets>turba</ets> tumult, disturbance, akin to
<ets>turbare</ets> to disturb. See <er>Trouble</er>, and cf.
<er>Disturb</er>, <er>Perturb</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not clear;
having suspended matter that scatters light passing through; having the
lees or sediment disturbed; roiled; muddy; thick; -- used of liquids of
any kind; <as>as, <ex>turbid</ex> water; <ex>turbid</ex>
wine.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On that strong, <qex>turbid</qex> water, a small boat,⟦br⟧
Guided by one weak hand, was seen to float.</q>
<rj><qau>Whittier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disturbed; confused; disordered.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ Such
<xex>turbid</xex> intervals that use to attend close prisoners.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turbidity</ent>⟦br⟧
